dcterms:creator: S. W. Golomb
L. R. Welch
R. M. Goldstein
A. W. Hales
dcterms:description: A dataset of m-sequences, which are pseudo-random sequences generated using linear feedback shift registers, widely used in communication systems.
dcterms:title: m-sequences

dcterms:creator: J. Lahtonen
dcterms:description: The Kasami code is a family of sequences with specific correlation properties, used in various communication applications.
dcterms:title: Kasami code

dcterms:creator: R. Gold
dcterms:description: Gold codes are a class of sequences that exhibit good correlation properties, derived from m-sequences, and are used in CDMA systems.
dcterms:title: Gold code

dcterms:creator: R. H. Barker
dcterms:description: Barker codes are sequences with good autocorrelation properties, used in radar and communication systems for synchronization.
dcterms:title: Barker code

dcterms:creator: P. V. Kumar
R. A. Scholtz
dcterms:description: Bent codes are sequences that maximize the minimum distance between sequences, providing good correlation properties.
dcterms:title: Bent code

dcterms:creator: A. Klapper
A. H. Chan
M. Goresky
dcterms:description: Gordon-Mills-Welch (GMW) sequences are designed to have low autocorrelation and are used in various signal processing applications.
dcterms:title: Gordon-Mills-Welch (GMW) sequence

dcterms:creator: Hai Deng
dcterms:description: Orthogonal polyphase sequence sets are used in radar systems to improve performance by minimizing interference.
dcterms:title: Orthogonal polyphase sequence sets

dcterms:creator: J. Liang
H. C. So
J. Li
A. Farina
dcterms:description: Unimodular sequences are designed to maintain constant modulus, which is important in communication systems to avoid distortion.
dcterms:title: Unimodular sequence

dcterms:creator: J. Song
P. Babu
D. P. Palomar
dcterms:description: Constant modulus sequences are designed to have a constant amplitude, which is crucial for minimizing interference in communication systems.
dcterms:title: Constant modulus sequences
